<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910404-0068</DOCNO><DOCID>910404-0068.</DOCID><HL>   Letters to the Editor:   Still Serving   Rural America</HL><DATE>04/04/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15</SO><CO>   LABOR X.GRE</CO><IN>MASS TRANSIT, BUS LINES, SUBWAYS, HIGHWAYS (TRA)</IN><NS>LABOR, PERSONNEL ISSUES, TRENDS, MANAGEMENT TECHNIQUES (LAB)</NS><LP>   In his March 7 &quot;Counterpoint&quot; column, Jack Sheinkman,president of the Amalgamated Clothing and Textile WorkersUnion, was incorrect on both his points about GreyhoundLines.   First, Greyhound bargained with the Amalgamated TransitUnion for four months before the union went on strike and hasparticipated in five sessions since the strike began. Thecompany still cannot afford to pay the ATU's exorbitant wagedemands for drivers.</LP><TEXT>   Second, Greyhound has not abandoned rural America. We areserving 95% of our pre-strike destinations.   Elizabeth P. Dunn   Public Relations Manager   Greyhound Lines Inc.   Dallas</TEXT></DOC>